TWO 5-GALLON CANS OF A HAZMAT SHIPMENT (RESIN SOLUTION) WERE DISCOVERED LEAKING AFTER BEGINNING TO UNLOAD MENLO TRUCK HTXI05 AT APPROXIMATELY 1500 CST, ON 06 SEP 2004.  THE DRIVER THAT DISCOVERED THE LEAKING SHIPMENT IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE SUPERVISOR ON DUTY.  THE SUPERVISOR CONTACTED THE SPILL CENTER AND MENLO WORLDWIDE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS.  A SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED BY THE CONTRACTOR, AND THE DAMAGED CONTAINERS AND WASTE PRODUCTS WERE DRUMMED AND STAGED FOR DISPOSAL.  INSPECTION OF PALLETIZED CANS INDICATED THAT THE CANS HAD SLIPPED LOOSE FROM THE BANDS THAT WERE HOLDING THE CANS BETWEEN UPPER AND LOWER WOODEN PALLETS.  ONCE LOOSENED, IT APPEARS THE CANS BOUNCED DURING TRANSPORT AND WERE SUBSEQUENTLY PUNCTURED.

column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT THE FONTANA, CA FACILITY ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. THE LEAK APPEARS TO BE COMING FROM THE BOTTOM SEAM.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP USING A SPILL PAD AND PACKED INTO A BAG.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO A SALVAGE CONTAINER AND PLACED IN OS & D.

WHILE AT A ROAD SIDE STOP THE DRIVER NOTICED A LIQUID BEGINNING TO LEAK OUT OF HIS TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS METHACRYLIC ACID.  THE DRIVER CALLED JEVIC HAZMAT (JHM) TO DISPATCH A SPILL RESPONSE CREW.  JHM CALLED OIL MOP INC. (OMI) TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL.  OMI ARRIVED ON SITE WITH A LIFT TRUCK TO OVERPACK THE DAMAGED CONTAINER.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP WITH SAND AND PACKED INTO DRUMS. ALL MATERIAL WAS LOADED BACK ONTO THE JEVIC TRAILER.
VALVE FAILED ON A TOTE.  MATERIAL WAS DRAINED INTO ANOTHER CONTAINER. SHIPPER RECEIVED FREIGHT BACK AT THERE FACILITY.

DRIVER OPENED BOTH SIDES OF FUEL TANKS ON VEHICLE BEING FUELED.  DRIVER WAS FILLING ONE SIDE AND FUEL WAS SPILLED OUT OF THE OPPOSITE SIDE.  DRIVER DAMMED THE SEWER BY PUTTING SPEEDY DRY AROUND IT, STOPPED THE FLOW OF THE FUEL AND CALLED INTO HIS DISPATCHER.  DISPATCHER NOTIFIED MANAGEMENT AND MANAGEMENT CALLED IN ROYAL ENVIRONMENTAL TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL.

SHIPMENT ARRIVED ON 09/10/2004, TOTAL WEIGHT OF SHIPMENT WAS 1329 LBS. 882LBS STACKED ON TOP OF 447 LBS THE PAILS WERE NOT ABLE TO HOLD THAT AMOUNT OF WEIGHT AND WERE CRUSHED BY THE BOXES ON TOP.  CHEMICAL SPILL REPORT COMPLETED AND PICTURES SENT TO ORIGIN/DESTINATION SERVICE CENTERS. SHIPPER NEEDS TO BE CONTACTED REGARDING THIS TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS WITH HEAVY SHIPMENTS.

DURING ROUTINE INSPECTION OF HAZMAT TANK CARS IN AVON YARD BY CSXT HAZMAT MANAGERS, ETCX 630507 WAS FOUND TO HAVE 10 OF 16 BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, BETWEEN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING NOZZLE AND THE MOUNTING FLANGE FOR THE TOP LOADING/UNLOADING FITTINGS.  PRODUCT ODOR ALERTED THE HAZMAT PERSONNEL TO THE LEAK DURING INSPECTION.  10 OF 16 BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED APPROXIMATELY 1/4 TURN.  THE LEAK STOPPED AND THE RAIL CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

WHILE CONDUCTING A ROUTINE COMPLIANCE INSPECTION AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S BOYLES YARD IN BIRMINGHAM, AL, CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER DISCOVERED A LCIX 2635, LOAD CARBON DIOXIDE, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, ON THE REPAIR TRACK VENTING FROM THE REGULATOR VALVE AS IN NORMAL.  THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER CHECKED THE PRESSURE ON THE CAR AND FOUND THE PRESSURE TO BE 200PSIG WHICH IS NOT SUFFICIENT TO CAUSE THE CAR TO VENT.  THE SHIPPER, PRAXAIR, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC AND THE PRAXAIR REPRESENTATIVE WAS CONNECTED TO CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER.  SEVERAL ATTEMPTS WERE MADE TO RESEAT THE REGULATOR VALVE BUT TO NO SUCCESS.  PRAXAIR SENT A TECHNICIAN FROM GADSDEN, AL TO INSPECT THE CAR.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE REGULATOR VALVE WAS PROBABLY DEFECTIVE AND WAS STUCK OPEN.  PRAXAIR SENT A TRUCK TO THE YARD TO BEGIN UNLOADING THE PRODUCT ON 09-06-04.  ONLY ONE TANKER LOAD OF PRODUCT, APPROXIMATELY 6,000 GALS, WAS TRANSLOADED FROM THE CAR AND IT WAS EMPTY.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE REGULATOR VALVE HAD BEEN LEAKING FOR SOMETIME AND AS MUCH AS 12,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE DEFECTIVE VALVE.

column168: A CUBIC YARD BOX OF HAZARDOUS WASTE, SOLID, N.O.S. (CHROMIUM) COLLAPSED DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS.  THE BOX HAD APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS OF FREE LIQUIDS ON THE TOP OF THE MATERIAL AND THE INNER LINER WAS NOT SEALED.  IT APPEARS THE LIQUID CAME TO THE TOP OF THE SOLIDS DURING TRANSPORTATION. THE BOX WAS REPACKAGE INTO STEEL DRUMS ON THE TRAILER.  THE SPILLAGE WAS ABSORBED USING OIL-DRY AN RECOVERED INTO DRUMS AS WELL.  THERE WAS NO SPILLAGE FROM THE TRAILER.  THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED BY GARNER ENVIRONMENTAL.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 6:00AM ON MONDAY, SEPT. 6TH, 2004, LEO ZDYB WAS TRAVELING NORTH ON HIGHWAY 64 IN RELIABLE TANK LINE UNIT 189/220.  LEO WAS LOADED WITH 9003 GALLONS OF CONVENTIONAL 87 OCTANE UNLEADED GAS.  THE DESTINATION WAS MORGANTON.  THE CUSTOMER WAS QUALITY OIL COMPANY.  THE SHIPPER WAS FLINT HILLS.  THE BOL WAS #0099948.  THE LOADING TERMINAL WAS KINDER MORGAN IN SPARTANBURG, NC.  WHILE TRAVELING NORTH BOUND ON HIGHWAY 64 APPROXIMATELY 10 MILES OUTSIDE OF RUTHERFORDTON, LEO STARTED INTO A CURVE THAT BORE TO THE LEFT.  FROM WHAT COULD BE DETERMINED FROM THE SCENE, THE RIGHT-SIDE TANDEM TIRES ON THE TRACTOR FELL OFF OF THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT.  LEO TRIED TO RIDE THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD UNTIL HE COULD SAFELY GET BACK ON THE PAVEMENT.  WHEN HE TRIED TO PULL THE TRACTOR BACK ON THE PAVEMENT, THE WEIGHT OF THE TRAILER SHIFTED AND LEO LOST CONTROL OF THE UNIT.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER BOTH ROLLED DOWN THE EMBANKMENT AND CAME TO REST IN THE CREEK BED JUST BESIDE A SMALL BRIDGE/CULVERT.  THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER BOTH BECAME ENGULFED IN FLAMES.  THE WRECK RESULTED IN THE DEATH OF RELIABLE TANK LINE DRIVER LEO ZDYB.  TRUCK 189 AND TRAILER 220 WERE TOTALLY DESTROYED.  THERE WAS VERY LITTLE PRODUCT LEFT IN THE TRAILER AS IT WAS LEFT ON ITS SIDE IN THE CREEK.  WHAT PRODUCT/WATER/FOAM THAT WAS LEFT IN THE TRAILER WAS PUMPED OUT BEFORE THE REMAINS OF THE TRAILER COULD BE REMOVED FROM THE CREEK.  WATER CONTAMINATION WAS MINIMAL DUE TO THE HEAVY FIRE THAT CONSUMED MOST OF THE PRODUCT.  THE BRIDGE, ROAD, LAND, AND TREES SURROUNDING THE WRECK AREA SUSTAINED SIGNIFICANT DAMAGE AND WILL POSSIBLY HAVE TO BE REMOVED AND REPLACED.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAMS (HIGHWAY PATROL, FIRE DEPARTMENT, EMS, ETC.)  RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY AND CONTAINED THE FIRE AND PRODUCT FROM FURTHER DAMAGE.  THE REPERCUSSIONS FROM THIS ACCIDENT ARE VERY EXTENSIVE AND WILL BE ONGOING.

THE DRUM WAS IN THE PROCESS OF BEING LOADED ON A TRAILER.  WHILE THE DRIVER WAS WAITING TO LOAD THE SHIPMENT ANOTHER DRIVER HAD A SHIPMENT ON HIS LIFT AND STRUCK THE DRUM WHILE MOVING DOWN THE DOCK.  THE DRUM AND SPILL WAS RECOUPED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND PLACED INTO THE HAZ-MAT BAY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND INFORMED OF THE DAMAGED AND THE DRIVER WILL BE ISSUED A WRITTEN WARNING AND RETRAINED ON THE FORKLIFT FOR THE PROPER HANDLING OF OUR CUSTOMERS FREIGHT.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS BEING PROCESSED FOR INBOUND DELIVERY WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED.  THE ITEM WAS BEING LOADED INTO A DELIVERY VAN WHEN THE DRIVER NOTICED SMOKE COMING FROM THE SIDES OF THE PACKAGE.  THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED WHICH CREATED A BACKDRAFT CAUSING THE INTERIOR TO INITIATE INTO A FIRE. HANDLING PERSONNEL MOVED IMMEDIATELY TO EXTINGUISH THE FIRE WITH A FIRE EXTINGUISHER  THE ITEM WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND FOUND TO CONTAIN A WEATHER TRACKING INSTRUMENT AND TWO TWELVE VOLT BATTERIES.  APPARENTLY THERE WAS SOME TYPE OF METALLIC STRIPPING IN THE PACKAGE THAT CAME INTO CONTACT WITH THE BATTERIES.  IT IS BELIEVED THAT AS THE TERMINALS OF THE BATTERIES WERE NOT COVERED THAT THE CONTACT OF THE TERMINALS WITH THE STRIPPING CAUSED THE BATTERIES TO ARC AND CATCH FIRE  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THIS INCIDENT.  TELEPHONE NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO SPECIAL AGENT JOHN BARRETT/FAA/ATL AT 14:06(CST) ON 09/13/2004.

TANK CAR UTLX 200279 WAS OBSERVED DRIPPING LIQUID FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR BY EMPLOYEES OF THE CARRIER IN THE CARRIER'S CLASSIFICATION YARD.  THE AREA AROUND THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE APPROPRIATE AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.  THE CARRIER CALLED AN EMERGENCY CONTRACTOR (REACT ENVIRONMENTAL) TO RESPOND AND INSPECT/REPAIR THE CAR AS NECESSARY.  UPON INSPECTION THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE NIPPLE FOR THE 3" LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS CRACKED AT THE JUNCTION BETWEEN THE THREADS OF THE NIPPLE AND THE 3" BALL VALVE. THE VALVE ITSELF WAS LOOSE AND PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING AROUND THE THREADS OF THE VALVE.  THE CONTRACTOR RELIEVED SOME OF THE INTERNAL PRESSURE IN THE CAR BY OPENING THE VAPOR LINE.  THE REDUCTION IN INTERNAL PRESSURE SLOWED THE LEAK CONSIDERABLY.  THE CONTRACTOR THEN REMOVED THE 3" BALL VALVE AND APPLIED EPOXY COMPOUND TO THE FRACTURED PORTION OF THE PIPE NIPPLE.  THE BLIND OUTLET PLUG WAS THEN THREADED INTO THE NIPPLE AND THE LEAK STOPPED. NO OTHER LEAKING FITTINGS WERE FOUND.  DUE TO THE VOLATILE NATURE AND HIGH EVAPORATION RATE OF THE PRODUCT, THERE WAS LITTLE SPILLED MATERIAL TO RECOVER.  SUBSEQUENT TO REPAIRING THE LEAKING VALVE, A MOVEMENT AUTHORITY WAS REQUESTED AND GRANTED TO MOVE THIS CAR TO SILSBEE, TX FOR FURTHER REPAIR.  (FRA-04090245)

ON SEPTEMBER 3, 2004, AT APPROXIMATELY 16:35 HOURS, A RAILWAY CAR IAPX 1015, LOADED WITH ARGON, REFRIGERATED LIQUID, 2.2, UN1951 WAS REPORTED LEAKING WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) KANSAS CITY, MISSOURI RAILYARD.  THE TANK CAR WAS ISOLATED, AND A CONTRACTED RESPONDER WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE AND FOUND THE EXHAUST VALVE PARTIALLY OPEN.  THE RESPONDER CLOSED THE VALVE, THUS CORRECTING THE RELEASE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES AND NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT.

THE SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED WITH A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON TOP OF THE DRUM WHILE BEING UNLOADED.  THE CAP ON THE DRUM WAS THIGHTEN AND THE DRUM WAS PLACE IN THE OS&D BAY OVER NIGHT TO MAKE SURE THE LEAK WAS STOPPED ON THE CONTAINER.  THE DRUM WAS CHECKED THE NEXT DAY AND THERE WAS NO LEAK. THE DRUM WAS THEN SENT ON TO DESTINATION.  THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED AND INFORMED OF THE PROBLEM TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING WITH FUTURE SHIPMENTS.

THE SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING WHILE BEING UNLOADED AND RECOUPED TO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WAS PLACED IN THE HAZ-MAT BAY FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  THE PAILS WHERE LOADED ON A SKID WRAPED WITH SHRINK WRAP AND LOADED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER.  DURING TRANSIT THE PALLET SHIFTED AND FELL HITTING THE WALL OF THE TRAILER CAUSING THE SPILL.  THERE WAS NOT ENOUGH DUNNAGE USED TO PROTECT THE FREIGHT FROM SHIFTING IN TRANSIT.  THE DRIVER WILL BE RETRAINED ON THE PROPER BLOCKING AND BRACING OF OUR CUSTOMERS SHIPMENTS.

DRIVER ARRIVED THE TULSA TERMINAL AND OPENED HIS TRAILER DOORS.  UPON OPENING THE DOORS A WHITE SUBSTANCE WAS SEEN AT THE SIDE OF THE SKID CONTAINING 5 STEEL DRUMS.  SUPERVISOR ON DUTY WAS NOTIFIED AND THE AREA RESTRICTED TO TRAFFIC.  SUPERVISOR DETECTED LEAK IN BOTTOM OF 1 OF THE DRUMS.  THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE A FORKBLADE PUNCTURE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM ABOUT 1/2 INCH IN SIZE.  DUE TO THE THICK CONSISTENCY OF THE SUBSTANCE, ONLY A SMALL PORTION (APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES) LEAKED UT. SUPERVISOR THEN CONTACTED THE MENLO ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT FOR GUIDANCE.  THE SUPERVISOR CONTACTED THE CONSIGNEE TO OBTAIN A MSDS SHEET FOR HELP IN DETERMINING THE PROPER CLEANUP PROCEDURE.  ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS USED TO ABSORB AND CONTAIN THE SUBSTANCE AND THEN PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG AND THE BAG PLACED IN A DISPOSAL CANISTER.

column42: SULFURIC ACID WITH MORE THAN 51 PERCENT ACID
column168: DRIVER LOADED TRAILER AT EL DORADO CHEMICAL IN EL DORADO, AR WITH 93 % SULFURIC ACID ENROUTE TO POTLACK CORP IN MCGEHEE, AR.  AFTER DRIVER HAD DRIVEN AWAY FROM EL DORADO CHEMICAL AN EMPLOYEE OF EL DORADO CHEMICAL NOTICE SOME DRIPS OF SULFURIC ACID ON THE GROUND AND CONTACTED UTI DISPATCHER TO EXPRESS THAT THE UTI TRAILER MIGHT BE LEAKING.  UTI DISPATCHER CONTACTED DRIVER BY PHONE AND HAD HIM STOP ENROUTE TO INVESTIGATE IF TRAILER WAS LEAKING.  DRIVER LOCATED A FEW DRIPS COMING FROM THE AIR PRESSURE BLOWDOWN LINE.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION THE DRIVER REALIZED THAT THE PRESSURE BLOW DOWN VALVE WAS NOT CLOSED ALLOWING PRODUCT TO ENTER BLOW DOWN LINE WHEN PRODUCT SURGED AGAINST IT DURING MOVEMENT WHICH ALLOWING SOME DRIPS TO EXIT BLOW DOWN LINE.  THE DRIVER CLOSED THE VALVE AND PROCEEDED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  ONCE THE DRIPPING WAS DISCOVERED THE ESCAPED PRODUCT HAD EVAPORATED WITHOUT CAUSING ANY DAMAGE TO PROPERTY OR POSING ANY FURTHER THREAT.

column168: THE DRIVER PICKED UP A LOAD OF CLEANING SUPPLIES IN PHOENIX, AZ.  AT THE FIRST DROP IN GALLUP, NM, THE DRIVER DID NOT SEE ANY SPILLAGE.  THE DRIVER THEN DROVE THE TRAILER TO ALBUQUERQUE NM, AND PARKED THE TRAILER IN THE RINCHEM YARD OVER THE WEEKEND.  NO LEAKAGE WAS NOTED WHEN THE DRIVER TOOK THE TRAILER MONDAY FOR ITS DELIVERY IN ALBUQUERQUE.  HE DROVE TWO MILES TO THE FINAL DROP POINT.  AS HE ENTERED THE YARD THERE, WORKERS TOLD HIM THAT HIS TRAILER WAS LEAKING.  PLASTIC BUCKETS WERE PLACED ON THE GROUND TO CATCH THE LEAKAGE AND RINCHEM EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED FOR CLEAN UP.  A PALLET IN THE MIDDLE OF THE LOAD HELD 36 5-GALLON PAILS OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE.  THE PAILS WERE STACKED THREE LEVELS HIGH AND WERE SHRINK-WRAP.  THEY HAD MOVED AROUND AND THE STACK HAD PARTIALLY TOPPLED. 12 PAILS HAD THEIR LIDS COME OFF OR LOOSENED AND MATERIAL HAD SPILLED OR SLOSHED OUT.  THE PAILS HAD BEEN PLACED ON SLATED WOODEN PALLETS, WHICH CONTRIBUTED TO THE PAILS TIPPING.  APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS HAD SPILLED. THE CLEANUP TEAM USED FLOOR DRY TO ABSORB THE LIQUID IN THE TRAILER.  A SMALL AMOUNT SPILLED ON THE GROUND WAS ALSO CLEANED UP.  ALL SPILLED AND ABSORBED MATERIAL WAS RETURNED TO THE RINCHEM YARD AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY.  IF A SOLID PLASTIC PALLET HAD BEEN USED THE BOTTOM PAILS WOULD NOT HAVE TIPPED.  THE INCIDENT WILL BE REVIEWED AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS WILL BE TAKEN TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE.

AROUND 8:00 AM EMPLOYEE HOOKED UP TO RAIL CAR OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID 32%, PRESSURIZED RAIL CAR AND PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD MATERIAL TO STORAGE TANK. AROUND 9:00 AM THE PVC VALVE CONNECTED TO THE RAILCAR CAME APART AT A UNION, RELEASING HYDROCHLORIC ACID AND FORMING A VAPOR CLOUD APPROXIMATELY 200 FT. IN THE AIR. EMPLOYEE CRAWLED OUT ON THE RAILCAR TO GET AWAY FROM VAPORS AND FELL TO THE GROUND.  HE WAS ABLE TO GET UP AND EVACUATE TO THE FRONT GATE WERE HE WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL.  RESPONSE PERSONNEL SUITED UP AND AROUND 9:10 HAD LEAK STOPPED.  FIRE DEPT. AND HAZ-MAT TEAM WERE DISPATCHED AT THE SCENE AND GAVE THE ALL CLEAR AT 10:30 AM.  IT WAS ESTIMATED THAT 280 GALS OF MATERIAL HAD SPILLED AND WAS CONTAINED IN THE DRAINAGE DITCH ALONG SIDE THE RAIL CAR.  THIS MATERIAL WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH  AND PUMPED TO A HOLDING TANK.  SOME MATERIAL HAD GOTTEN BY THE CONTAINMENT INTO THE STORM SEWER.  NU-WAY ENVIRONMENTAL WAS CALLED IN TO FLUSH OUT STORM DRAINS.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY AT SYN MAR PRODUCTS, AT 83 ELLINGTON INDUSTRIAL PARK, IN ELLINGTON, CONNECTICUT, ONE 2,500 POUND PLASTIC TOTE ROLLED OFF THE TRUCK AND THE TOP BROKE OFF THE TOTE.  APROXIMATELY 138 GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  THE ELLINGTON FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE AND RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  TRI-S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. OF ELLINGTON, CONNECTICUT WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE MAHOGANY COMPANY DRIVER BUILT A DIKE TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT AND ALSO USED A SHOVEL TO PLACE THE NON-CONTAMINATED PRODUCT INTO 2, 30 GALLON AND 2, 55 GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS, WHICH WERE SENT BACK TO THE MAHOGANY COMPANY FACILITY IN MAYS LANDING, NEW JERSEY.  TRI-S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND LYME TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT THAT HAD AFFECTED THE ASPHALT SURFACE.  TRI-S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. COVERED THE AFFECTED ASPHALT WITH POLY SHEETING. TRI-S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. USED A BACKHOE TO REMOVE APPROXIMATELY 4 CUBIC YARDS OF IMPACTED SOIL AND RIP-RAP FROM THE AFFECTED SITE.  TRI-S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. LINED THE EXCAVATED AREA WITH POLY SHEETING TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER CONTAMINATION UNTIL THEY COULD RETURN AT A LATER DATE TO BACKFILL THE EXCAVATED AREA. ON OCTOBER 4, 2004, TRI-S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. RETURNEDTO THE SITEAND SCRAPED UP THE IMPACTED ABSORBENT MATERIALS AND LIME AND PLACED THEM INTO 5, 1 CUBIC YARD BOXES ALONG WITH THE IMPACTED SOIL AND RIP-RAP FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.  TRI-S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. POWER WASHED THE AFFECTED AREA AND PLACED THE IMPACTED LIQUIDS INTO EIGHT, 55 GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  ON OCTOBER 5, 2004, TRI-S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. BACKFILLED THE EXCAVATED AREA AND PLACED DOWN NEW TOP SOIL, GRASS SEED AND RIP-RAP TO RETURN THE SITE TO IT'S PRE-EXISTING CONDITION.  TRI-S ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE EIGHT, 55 GALLON DRUMS OF IMPACTED LIQUID AND FIVE, 1 YARD CUBIC BOXES OF IMPACTED ABSORBENT MATERIALS, LIME SOIL AND RIP-RAP.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

CSX TRANSPORTATION'S POLICE COMMUNICATION CENTER RECEIVED A REPORT FROM CHEMTREC THAT A TANK CAR, GATX 55081, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED OTHER REGULATED SUBSTANCES, LIQUID, NOS (METHYLENE DIPHENYL DIISOCYANATE) WAS LEAKING VAPORS FROM THE TOP IN A TRAIN JUST OUTSIDE CSXT'S GENTILLY YARD IN NEW ORLEANS, LA.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER CONTACTED CAPTAIN HELMERS OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ON SCENE.  CAPT. HELMER ADVISED CAR WAS VENTING VAPORS BETWEEN THE MANWAY COVER AND THE GASKET AND THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR AROUND THE CAR.  CAPT. HELMER ALSO ADVISED THAT THEY HAD INITIATED AN EVACUATION OF NEARBY RESIDENCES AS A PRECAUTION.  CSXT PERSONNEL AND AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. STATE AND FEDERAL SPILL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THREE OF THE MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS WAS LESS THAN WRENCH TIGHT ALLOWING VAPORS TO ESCAPE.  THE MANWAY BOLT WAS TIGHTENED AND THE TRAIN WAS RELEASED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO MOVE INTO THE GENTILLY YARD WHERE THE CAR WAS PLACED ON THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ISOLATION TRACK ALONG WITH THE ADJACENT TANK CAR, UTLX 49638, LOAD FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS (CRUDE TERPENTINE). FURTHER INVESTIGATION BY CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MANAGER AND THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET ON THE UTLX 49638 WAS NOT SEATED PROPERLY AND THE GASKET WAS DETERIORATED WHICH ALLOWED VAPORS TO ESCAPE FROM THE CAR.  THE CONTRACTOR INSTALLED A NEW MANWAY COVER GASKET AND PROPERLY SECURED THE CAR.  BOTH CARS ARE ON HOLD AT GENTILLY YARD FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.

UTLX 49638, LOAD FLAMMABLE LIQUID NOS (CRUDE TURPENTINE) WAS ENTRAINED NEXT TO A GATX 55081, RESIDUE LAST CONTAINED OTHER REGULATED SUBSTANCE, LIQUID, NOS (METHYLENE DIPHENYL DIISOCYANATE) IN A CSX TRANSPORTATION TRAIN IN NEW ORLEANS, LA.  CHEMTREC REPORTED TO CSXT'S POLICE COMMUNICATION CENTER THAT THE NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD RESPONDED TO A REPORT THAT THE THE GATX 55081 WAS LEAKING VAPORS AND THERE WAS A STRONG ODOR.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE VAPOR LEAK ON THE GATX 55081.  ONCE THE LEAK WAS REPAIRED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT RELEASED THE TRAIN AND IT WAS PULLED INTO GENTILLY YARD.  THE GATX 55081 AND THE UTLX 49638 WERE MOVED TO THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ISOLATION TRACK FOR FURTHER INSPECTION.  THE MANWAY COVER GASKET ON THE UTLX 49638 WAS FOUND TO BE SEATED IMPROPERLY AND THE GASKET ITSELF WAS DETERIORATED WHICH PERMITTED TURPENTINE VAPORS TO ESCAPE THE CAR.  A NEW MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS PROPERLY INSTALLED AND THE MANWAY COVER WAS SECURED.   THE VAPOR RELEASE STOPPED.  THE SHIPPER, INLAND PAPERBOARD, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE CONDITION OF THE CAR.

NATX21735, LOAD CYCLOHEXANONE, WHICH HAD BEEN REPORTED TO BE DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN SELKIRK, NY ON 09-15-2004, WAS DISCOVERED AGAIN TO BE DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE (BOV) CAP.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR RESPONDED TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE TOP OPERATING ROD FOR THE BOV WAS FOUND TO BE CLOSED AND THE BOV CAP WAS WRENCH TIGHT.  THE BOV WAS DRAINED AND THE CAP WAS REMOVED.  THE TEMPORARY TEFLON ROPE GASKET WAS REMOVED AND A STANDARD NEOPRENE GASKET WAS INSTALLED.  THE BOV CAR WAS INSTALLED WRENCH TIGHT AND THE LEAK STOPPED. THE CONTRACTOR ALSO PLACED LUTING MATERIAL IN THE PACKING GLAND TO ENSURE THE TOP OPERATING ROD WAS HELD SECURELY.

CSX TRANSPORTATION'S TRAINMASTER IN GREENWOOD, SC, REPORTED THAT ACFX94902, LOAD HEXAMETHYLENEDIAMINE, WAS SITTING ON THE RUN A ROUND TRACK OUTSIDE OF THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY AND WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP.  THE CONSIGNEE, SOLUTIA, INC, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT AND THEY RESPONDED TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  ACCORDING TO SOLUTIA REPRESENTATIVES, WHEN THEY ARRIVED AT THE CAR IT WAS ACTIVELY LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE TOP.  THE PRODUCT FLOWED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR WAS DRIPPING ONTO THE BALLAST IN THE TRACK.  THEY DISCOVERED THAT THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING OVER THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE WAS OPEN AND PRODUCT WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE LIQUID LINE BECAUSE THE THE BALL VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE VALVE CAP WAS LESS THAN FINGER TIGHT.  SOLUTIA PERSONNEL CLOSED THE LIQUID VALVE AND MADE THE VALVE CAP WRENCH TIGHT AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED THE SHIPPER, SOLUTIA, INC OF THE INCIDENT AND THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.  THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED INTO THE SOLUTIA FACILITY SO THAT IT COULD BE WASHED DOWN AND UNLOADED.  CSXT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO NEUTRALIZE THE TRUCK BALLAST WHERE THE CAR HAD DRIPPED PRODUCT.

THE LEAK OF THE RESIN SOLUTION WAS INITIALLY NOTICED BY A WERNER ENTERPRISES DRIVER DURING A PRE-TRIP INSPECTION OF THE LOADED TRAILER AT THE WERNER/JENKINS FACILITY IN NASHVILLE, TN.  THE DRIVER NOTED A SMALL LEAK AT THE REAR OF THE TRAILER AND IMMEDIATELY CALLED WERNER ENTERPRISES IN OMAHA, NE TO REPORT THE SPILL AT 07:20 CST.  UPON RECEIPT OF THE INITIAL REPORT OF THE SPILL, WERNER ENTERPRISES CALLED A SPILL CONTRACTOR.  AT 12:55CST, THE SPILL RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND DETERMINED WHAT HAD SPILLED AND WHAT PPE WOULD BE REQUIRED TO ENTER THE TRAILER.  THE SPILL TEAM ENTERED THE TRAILER WEARING LEVEL "C" PPE.  THE TEAM CHECKED AND REMOVED ALL UNDAMAGED DRUMS TO ANOTHER TRAILER.  ONE (1) DRUM WAS FOUND TO HAVE A DENT AND A ONE (1) INCH PUNCTURE IN THE BODY OF THE DRUM, ON THE "CHIME" OR ROLLING-RING AS IT IS CALLED.  APPROXIMATELY TWO (2) GALLONS OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED ON TO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO AN EIGHTY-FIVE (85) GALLON SALVAGE DRUM AND RELOADED ONTO THE TRAILER FOR TRANSPORT TO THE FINAL DESTINATION.  THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED UTILIZING ABSORBENT PADS AND ACETONE.  UPON FINAL CLEAN UP, THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS RELEASED BACK TO THE WERNER ENTERPRISES DRIVER.

column168: THE DRIVER REPORTED SOMETHING CAUGHT HIS ATTENTION TO THE LEFT OF HIS TRUCK.  HIS TRUCK LEFT THE ROADWAY TO THE RIGHT.  THE EMBANKMENT DROPS SIGNIFICANTLY AT THIS POINT.  HE HIT A POWER POLE WITH THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE CARGO TANK, BREAKING THE POWER POLE.  HE CAME BACK ON THE HIGHWAY, THE LOAD SHIFTED TO THE RIGHT AND THE TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED ON IT'S SIDE AND SLID ON THE ROADWAY RUPTURING THE CARGO TANK.  THE DRIVER CALLED OUR BUHL OFFICE, THEY CALLED 911.  THE FIRE DEPT OF BUHL, TWIN FALLS COUNTY SHERIFF AND MAGIC VALLEY REGIONAL AMBULANCE SERVICE ARRIVED BETWEEN 9:15 A.M. AND 9:30 A.M.  THE DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO MAGIC VALLEY REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER FOR TREATMENT WHERE HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED.  BUHL FIRE DEPT. CLOSED THE ROAD AND SPREAD SAND ON THE ROADWAY TO CONTAIN THE LEAKING DIESEL FUEL. THE REGIONAL HAZMAT TEAM FROM POCATELLO, IDAHO WAS CALLED IN THEY ARRIVED APPROXIMATELY 5 HOURS AFTER THE ACCIDENT.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN CAUTIONED NOT TO BE DISTRACTED WHEN TRANSPORTING DIESEL FUEL AND GASOLINE.

column168: THE EAGLE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE AT FASMART #21 IN QUINTON, VA.  THE SPILL WAS A RESULT OF A MALFUNCTION IN THE VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM OF THE GASOLINE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK UST.  NO PRODUCT REPORTEDLY GOT INTO THE STATE WATERS OR STORM DRAINS.  THERE WERE NO WATERWAYS AFFECTED. INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICES (IMS) WAS CALLED BY ACTION ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND TO THE SPILL.  ACCORDING TO IMS, THE SPILL AREA HAD BEEN COVERED WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL BY THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT. UPON THERE ARRIVAL.  IMS RECOVERED THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND A MINOR AMOUNT OF SOIL THAT WAS AFFECTED BY THE RELEASE.  NO FURTHER ACTION SHOULD BE REQUIRED.  THE VA DEPT. OF ENV. QUALITY AND THE FIRE DEPT. WERE NOTIFIED OF THE RELEASE.  TO TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS AGAINST THIS OCCURRING AGAIN.  EAGLE WILL REQUEST THAT THE CUSTOMER REPAIR THE VAPOR RECOVERY SYSTEM.

column168: HEAT EXPANSION.  CAUSED SEEPAGE THROUGH THE LIDS.

AN OPERATOR WAS ATTENDING THE LOADING OF A TANK CAR WITH WASTE OIL THAT IS CLASSIFIED AS A HAZARDOUS WASTE.  THE TANK CAR HAD BEEN PARTIALLY LOADED EARLIER IN THE DAY AND THE LOADING OPERATION WAS RESUMED AT 4:35 P.M. ON SEPTEMBER 18, 2004.  THE OPERATOR LEFT THE LOADING AREA TO MOVE AN OUTBOUND TANK TRUCK TO THE WEIGH SCALES.  WHEN HE RETURNED THE MATERIAL WAS OVERFLOWING FROM THE TANK CAR, RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE AND ONTO THE CONCRETE PAD NEXT TO THE TRACKS AND INTO THE TRACK PAN UNDER THE RAIL CAR.  THE TEMPERATURE WAS 70 F AND THE WIND OUT OF THE NNW ABOUT 8 MPH.  258 POUNDS OF WASTE OIL WAS SPILLED ON TO THE CONCRETE AND TRACK PAN, WITH ABOUT 5 POUNDS RUNNING INTO THE GRAVEL.  THE LOADING OPERATION WAS IMMEDIATELY STOPPED.  A VACUUM SUCKER AND ABSORBENT PADS WERE USED TO PICK UP THE WASTE OIL ON THE CONCRETE PAD.  ALL VISUAL EVIDENCE OF THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP. THE WASTE OIL WAS PUT INTO THE <90 DAY STORAGE TANK AND THE PADS WERE PLACED IN CONTAINERS AND INCINERATED AT THE ON-SITE RCRA HAZARDOUS WASTE INCINERATOR.  APPROXIMATELY 1 CUBIC YARD OF SOIL AND GRAVEL AROUND THE SPILL AREA WAS REMOVED FOR DISPOSAL OFF-SITE AT AN APPROVED FACILITY. ANALYSIS OF THE SOIL AND GRAVEL SHOWED IT TO BE NON-HAZARDOUS.  THE DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS LESS THAN 10 MINUTES.

DRIVER HAD CALLED FROM A DELIVERY POINT IN EL PASO, TEX. TO REPORT THAT THERE IS A STRONG ODOR OF ALCOHOL IN HIS TRAILER.  HE HAS CHECKED THE LOAD OVER BUT CANNOT SEE ANY EVIDENCE OF LEAKAGE.  HE AND THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST CONCLUDED THAT IT MAY BE VENTING DUE TO AMBIENT TEMPERATURE CHANGES.  HE CONTINUED ON HIS WAY.  AT A TRUCK STOP IN DEMING, N.M. HE CHECKED THE LOAD AGAIN.  THIS TIME HE FOUND LIQUID ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  IT IS COMING FROM A CRACK IN A DENT IN ONE OF THE DRUM'S ROLLING HOOPS.  THE DRIVER SET THE DRUM ONTO ITS SIDE AND SECURED IT TO THE TRAILER WALL.  HE ACQUIRED SOME EPOXY AND PATCHED THE CRACK.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO HAVE THE DRIVER PROCEED TO A CONTRACTOR'S NEARBY FACILITY.  ON ARRIVAL THERE THE CONTRACTOR PUT THE LEAKING DRUM INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE DRIVER THEN CONTINUED ON HIS WAY.

DRIVER CALLED TO REPORT THAT HE IS IN A TRUCK STOP.  HE OBSERVED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM UNDER THE TRAILER DOOR.  HE OPENED THE DOOR AND FOUND THAT THE LIQUID HAD COME FROM THE TOPS OF TWO TOTES.  THE FILL CAPS ON THE TWO TOTES APPEAR TO BE CROSS THREADED ON, CREATING AN INCOMPLETE CLOSURE OF THE CONTAINER.  THE DRIVER PUT SPILL PADS ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AND ON THE GROUND.  THEY HAVE PICKED UP THE SPILLAGE.  HE STATES THAT HE CAN LOOSEN THE CAPS AND PUT THEM ON CORRECTLY, HOWEVER THERE ARE SEALS ON THEM WHICH WOULD HAVE TO BE BROKEN IN ORDER TO DO IT.  HAZMAT CONTACTED MR. DICK GEIB, A REPRESENTATIVE OF THE SHIPPER.  MR. GEIB AUTHORIZED BREAKING THE SEALS. DRIVER CALLED BACK TO REPORT THAT HE REMOVED AND CORRECTLY REPLACED BOTH CAPS.  THEY APPEAR TO BE PROPERLY IN PLACE NOW.  HE HAS PICKED UP THE SPILL PADS AND HAS PUT THEM, ALONG WITH THE SPILL KIT GLOVES INTO THE KIT'S PLASTIC BAG.  HE WILL TAKE THEM WITH HIM AND LEAVE THEM AT A JEVIC FACILITY.  HE WILL MONITOR THE CONDITION OF THE TOTES PERIODICALLY.

DURING UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE, THEIR FORK LIFT STRUCK AND PUNCTURED ONE DRUM.  ABOUT TWO GALLONS OF PRODUCT ESCAPED BEFORE THEY PUT THE DRUM ONTO ITS SIDE.  THE CONSIGNEE'S RECEIVER WAS PROPOSING TO RINSE THE TRAILER OUT WITH WATER.  HAZMAT ADVISED THEM THAT WATER SHOULD NOT BE USED AS THE MATERIAL IS HEAVIER THAN WATER AND INSOLUBLE IN WATER.  IT DOES EVAPORATE RAPIDLY.  ABSORBING THE SPILLAGE USING OIL DRY IS RECOMMENDED.  THE OIL DRY SHOULD BE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

DURING UNLOADING AT THE CONSIGNEE, THEY OBSERVED SOME LIQUID ON THE TOP OF ONE DRUM.  IT WAS FOUND TO BE ESCAPING THROUGH A LOOSE BUNG.  THE CONSIGNEE REFUSED THE DRUM.  THE DRIVER TIGHTENED THE BUNG AND WILL RETURN IT TO J1. NO PRODUCT REACHED THE TRAILER FLOOR.

AFTER SPEAKING TO ALL PRESENT AND CHECKING THE CAMERA'S, THE FOLLOWING APPEARS TO HAVE HAPPENED:  JAL PALLET NUMBER PMC27222JL WAS BEING TAKEN OFF SYSTEM, HOWEVER THERE WAS A FORKLIFT WHICH HAD BEEN LEFT UNATTENDED WITH ITS BLADES IN THE DOWN POSITION BUT TILTED.  AS THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR (VIDEL HERNANDEZ) WAS PULLING THE PALLET OFF, HE ATTEMPTED TO TURN THE FORKLIFT HOWEVER IN DOING SO THE PALLET HIT THE FORKLIFT WHICH HAD BEEN LEFT NEXT TO THE SYSTEM.  HE LATER AFTER DISCUSSING IT WITH HIM FELT THAT THE PALLET HAD SLID, HE DECIDED TO GO IN UNDER IT IN AN ATTEMPT TO PICK IT BACK UP.  IN DOING SO, HE PUSHED THE PALLET IN AND ONTO THE FORK BLADE WHICH HAD BEEN LEFT UP CAUSING THE FORKLIFT BLADE TO PUNCHER THE STEEL JERRICAN WHICH HAD BEEN FLOOR LOADED.  BECAUSE THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR HAD YET TO SEE THE JEEP BEHIND THE PALLET HE ASSUMED IT WAS HEAVIER THAN EXPECTED CAUSING HIM TO ATTEMPT TO GO IN DEEPER WITH HIS BLADES, AS THIS TIME HE NOTICED THE RESISTANCE AND GOT DOWN FROM THE FORKLIFT TO CHECK. AFTER NOTICING THE LEAK HE ADVISED HIS SUPERVISOR WHO INFORMED JAL MOD AND FOLLOWED UP BY CALLING THE BREAKDOWN MANAGER AND THE WAREHOUSE MANAGER JOE RAMIREZ.  JOE CALLED ME TO ADVISE AND ONCE I ARRIVED I ASSUMED THE RESPONSIBILITY OF ATTAINING THE UN NUMBER, CLASS AND PIECES DAMAGED.  I THEN CHECK MY EMERGENCY RESPONSE BOOK AND FOLLOWED THE PROCEDURES BY PLACING OIL DRY MATERIAL OVER THE SPILL AND REMOVING THE NET AND PLASTIC. AT THIS POINT ED HAWKINS, MOD FOR JAL, ADVISED HE HAD FOLLOWED HIS PROTOCOL AND HAD CONTACTED THE LOCAL EMERGENCY TEAM.  HE WAS TOLD NOT TO HAVE ANYONE TOUCH IT AND TO VACATE THE AREA.  WE THEN SECTIONED OFF THE EVA SIDE USING STRAPS AND WAITED FOR THE RESPONSE TEAM.  AFTER ARRIVAL I ADVISED THE CHIEF OF THE SITUATION AND WHAT WE HAD DID TO THAT POINT.  WE SUPPLIED OUR CHEMICAL SPILL CANISTERS AND SEVERAL BAGS OF OIL DRY AND AWAITED THE HAZ MAT RESPONSE TEAM HE CALLED.  I FOLLOWED UP BY CONTACTING OUR EMERGENCY SPILL CENTER AND ADVISING OF ALL INFORMATION.  LASTLY THE HAZ MAT RESPONSE TEAM CLEANED THE AREA ON OUR BEHALF AND ADVISED THAT OUR SPILL CENTER DISPOSE OF THE MATERIAL AS SOON POSSIBLE.  PER MY DISCUSSION WITH THE CENTER THEY WILL BE HERE ON MONDAY TO DISPOSE OF IT.  NO ONE WAS HURT AND OR NEEDED TREATMENT. column62: Defective Component or Device; Corrosion - Exterior
column168: WHEN I ARRIVED TO WORK ON 9-10-2004 THERE WAS A TOTE SITTING ON THE DOCK GOING TO SAN BERNADINO ON A CLEARANCE BILL WITH 1 OTHER TOTE.  WHEN I MOVED THE TOTE TO BE LOADED THERE WAS A SMALL PUDDLE OF FLUID ON THE DOCK UNDER THE TOTE.  I THEN CALLED MIKE SORENESON IN THE SAFETY DEPARTMENT AND TOLD HIM WHAT HAPPENED AND WHAT I PLANED TO DO.  I THEN ISOLATED THE TOTE AND PUT IT ON A SHEET OF CARDBOARD TO VERIFY IF IT WAS THE TOTE OR JUST SOME OTHER FLUID.  AFTER ABOUT 10 MINUTE I RECHECKED IT AND IN FACT IT WAS LEAKING SO I CALLED THE 24 HOUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE NUMBER AND THEY TOLD ME TO ISOLATE THE SPILL AND THEY WOULD CALL THE SHIPPER TO SEE WHAT STEPS WOULD BE TAKEN.  THE SHIPPED BJ UNICHEM TOLD ME THAT THEY WOULD SEND A LOCAL VENDOR FROM THERE LOCAL OFFICE TO COME AND FIX THE LEAK.  THE REPAIR MAN ARRIVED AND TRIED TO FIX THE LEAK BUT IT WAS IN THE WELD AND IT COULD NOT BE FIXED SO I HELD THE FREIGHT TO BE REPAIRED ON 9-13-2004.  ON 9-13-2004 THE REPAIR MAN CAME AND PUMPED THE REMAINING FLUID INTO A NEW TOTE AND THE I SHIPPED IT ON TO SAN BERNADINO.

column168: PATTY UPRR, REPORTED CONTAINER OOLU 526346 WAS LEAKING AT THE NORTH YARD IN NORTH SALT LAKE, UT.  LEON HENDRICKSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AT 04:00 PM, HENDRICKSON REPORTED THE CONTAINER HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 20 POUNDS OF PRODUCT DUE TO FAILED BLOCKING AND BRACING.  CHEMTREC, STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE. PACIFIC WEST COMPLETED THE CLEAN UP AND DECONTAMINATED THE CAR.

KEN, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED AN ODOR IN THE AVONDALE YARD, IN AVONDALE, LA.  KEN ADVISED THE TANK CAR WAS LOCATED ON YARD SEVEN, TRACK 111.  THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER OF FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  HE INSTRUCTED RMCC TO MAKE A SHIPPER NOTIFICATION TO CHEMTREC, AND STATE NOTIFICATIONS.   AT 09:12 AM, ROBINSON REPORTED STEVE DENNIS, DOW CHEMICAL EMERGENCY COORDINATOR, AND TOMMY MCGEE, UNION CARBIDE DISTRIBUTION MANAGER, WERE ENROUTE TO INSPECT THE TANKCAR.  AT 09:19 AM, DAVID YOUNG, ENVIRONMENTAL COUNSEL, INSTRUCTED RMCC TO NOTIFY CTEH.  AT 09:56 AM THE BRIDGE CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SCENE.  UPDATE: THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE LOOSE, CAUSING THE TANKCAR TO RELEASE VAPOR.  THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED BY DOW/UNION CARBIDE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS.

ON 0310 HRS ON 9-5-04 FRANK LERCH, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED OF A VEHICLE CROSSING ACCIDENT AT THE GOLIAD CROSSING NEAR MCFADDIN, TX.  TRAIN MBVHO-03, LEAD LOCOMOTIVE UP 9293, NEAR MILE POST 206.16 ON THE BROWNSVILLE SUBDIVISION.  MR URBAN STATED TRAIN WAS STOPPED WHEN THE VEHICLE COLLIDED WITH A TANK CAR WHICH CONTAINED FLAMMABLE MATERIAL.  MR. URBAN ADVISED THE VEHICLE WAS ON FIRE AND THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE WAS TRAPPED INSIDE.  ADDITIONALLY, MR. URBAN STATED LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED AND ENROUTE.  AT 02:40 AM, THE REFUGIO POLICE DEPARTMENT, REPORTED THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE WAS FATALLY INJURED AS THE VEHICLE HAD BURST INTO FLAMES UPON IMPACT.  THERE WERE NO REPORTS OF LEAKAGE OR DAMAGE TO THE TANK CAR.  ALL STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 03:12 AM THE TANK CAR STRUCK WAS IDENTIFIED AS CELX 23256, A RESIDUE EMPTY LAST CONTAINING BUTYRALDEHYDE.  AFTER IDENTIFICATION OF THE TANK, RMCC MADE NOTIFICATION TO CELANESE CHEMICAL VIA CHEMTREC.  IRA GORDEN SHIPPING TEAM LEADER RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO FURTHER INSPECT THE TANK CAR PRIOR TO PULLING THE DAMAGED VEHICLE CLEAR. MR. GORDEN NOTED THE SECONDARY TWO INCH BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS DAMAGED, HOWEVER THE PRIMARY INTERNAL ANGLE BALL VALVE WAS CLOSED AND INTACT.  AFTER DETERMINING IT WAS SAFE TO PULL THE VEHICLE CLEAR OF THE TANK CAR, EXTRACTION OF THE CAR BEGAN.  WHILE THE CAR WAS BEING PULLED CLEAR, THERE WAS A SUDDEN RELEASE OF INTERNAL PRESSURE FROM THE CAR AND A STRONG RESIDUE ODOR OF BUTYRALDEHYDE RELEASED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  AT 07:15 AM TOM COOPER, TRACK SUPERVISOR REPORTED WHEN THE RELEASE OCCURRED THERE WERE 23 TRACK MAINTENANCE EMPLOYEES APPROXIMATELY 1/4 MILE SOUTHEAST OF THE CAR WHO SHORTLY AFTER THE RELEASE COMPLAINED OF SORE THROATS AND HEADACHES.  ALL EMPLOYEES WERE IMMEDIATELY TAKEN THE VICTORIA HOSPITAL FOR A WELLNESS CHECK.  AFTER THE VAPOR RELEASE, AN INSPECTION OF THE CAR BY THE LOCAL CARMAN DEVELOPED THE RELEASE OCCURRED AS THE CAR WAS BEING PULLED CLEAR AND THE OPERATING HANDLE TO THE INTERNAL BALL VALVE ON THE TANK CAR CAUGHT ONTO PART OF THE MOTOR VEHICLE AND WAS PARTIALLY OPENED, CAUSING A RELEASE OF ODOR INTO THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  THE VALVE WAS THEN CLOSED, AND THE OPERATING HAD REMOVED.  AFTER WORKING ON THE CAR, THE CARMAN ALSO HAD A WELLNESS CHECK AT THE REFUGIO MEDICAL CLINIC, AND RETURNED TO WORK.  AFTER THE ODOR RELEASE OCCURRED, CTEH (CENTER FOR TOXICOLOGY & ENVIRONMENTAL HEALTH) PERSONNEL WERE NOTIFIED.  MR LERCH WAS ADVISED THAT EIGHTEEN TRACK EMPLOYEES WERE EVALUATED AT THE HOSPITAL AND NONE WERE FOUND TO HAVE ANY INHALATION INJURIES.  THE EMPLOYEES WERE RELEASED AND RETURNED TO WORK WITHOUT ANY RESTRICTIONS.  ON 9-7-04, MGR LERCH INSPECTED CAR CELX 23256 NOTING ALL CLOSURES TO BE SECURE.  CAR WAS HOME SHOPPED FOR INSPECTION AND NECESSARY REPAIRS.

AT 2100HRS ON 9-5-04 CTS MGR LERCH WAS CONTACTED BY THE RMCC AND ADVISED THAT GARY DAVIS, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS HAD REPORTED TANK CAR GATX 58003 LOCATED IN TRACK 230 SETTEGAST YARD; HOUSTON, TX.  TO BE LEAKING.  AFTER BEING NOTIFIED, MGR LERCH INSTRUCTED RMCC TO MAKE SHIPPER NOTIFICATION VIA CHEM-TREC.  ON ARRIVAL MGR LERCH NOTED SIDES OF CAR TO BE SLIGHTLY MOIST FROM PRODUCT RELEASE.  INSPECTION OF THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY REVEALED THAT THE RUPTURE DISK (ZOOK #165) HAD BEEN RUPTURED.  MGR LERCH REPLACED DISK WITH SAME KIND, AND RELEASED CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  AT 2200 HRS MGR LERCH SPOKE TO SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE RANDY OAKLEY, PLANT MANAGER FOR SOUTHERN IONICS ADVISING HIM OF THE RELEASE. CAUSE OF DISK FAILURE UNKNOWN.  THERE WERE NO DRAINS, WATERWAYS IMPACTED OR REPORTED INJURIES RESULTING FROM THIS RELEASE.

ON 09/20/04 @ 4:45 AM, JERRY HOSACK WAS INJURED IN A SPILL WITH SULFURIC ACID AT SATCO IN TAMPA, FL.  JERRY HOSACK RECEIVED INJURIES REQUIRING HIM TO BE TRANSPORTED BY AMBULANCE TO TAMPA GENERAL HOSPITAL.  CTL'S SAFETY MANAGER WAS NOTIFIED BY CTL DISPATCH THAT A DRIVER FOR CTL HAD BEEN EXPOSED TO SULFURIC ACID FROM A OFF-LOADING LINE THAT HAD COME DISCONNECTED FROM THE REAR DISCHARGE VALVE ASSEMBLY ON THE TRAILER.  CTL'S SAFETY MANAGER ARRIVED ON SCENE WHERE THE SPILL OCCURRED AND FOUND THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND THE UNLOADING SCALE HAD BEEN WASHED DOWN.  CTL'S SAFETY MANAGER CALLED TAMPA GENERAL HOSPITAL TO GET A STATUS ON THE DRIVER, BUT THERE WAS NO INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THAT TIME.  CTL'S SAFETY MANAGER THEN INSPECTED THE DISCHARGE VALVE AND THE HOSE CONNECTION AND FOUND THAT THE CAM LOCKS ON THE DISCHARGE VALVE ASSEMBLY HAD BEEN INSTALLED IMPROPERLY.  AT THIS TIME CTL'S SAFETY MANAGER NOTIFIED THE VP OF LOSS PREVENTION FOR CTL TO INFORM HIM OF WHAT TAKEN PLACE AND HIS INITIAL FINDINGS.  AN INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE TRAILER HAD NOT BEEN USE PRIOR TO THIS INCIDENT.  THE REPAIRS WHERE PERFORMED BY AN OUTSIDE VENDOR IN TAMPA THAT MAINTAINS CTL'S EQUIPMENT.  THE DRIVER WAS WEARING ALL OF THE REQUIRED PPE EQUIPMENT AT THE TIME THE INCIDENT OCCURRED.  IT APPEARS THE DRIVER HAD TURNED HIS BACK TO THE DISCHARGE ASSEMBLY JUST PRIOR TO IT FALLING.  THE PRODUCT HIT THE DRIVER IN THE BACK KNOCKING HIS HARD HAT OFF AND KNOCKING HIM DOWN TO THE GROUND AND COVERING HIM WITH SULFURIC ACID.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY GOT UP AND CLOSED THE EXTERNAL VALVE ON THE DISCHARGE ASSEMBLY.  THE DRIVER THEN GOT UNDER THE SAFETY SHOWER AND BEGIN TO REMOVE HIS PPE AND PERSONAL CLOTHING.  AFTER THE DRIVER HAD BEEN UNDER THE SAFETY SHOWER FOR AWHILE HE WENT INTO THE CONTROL ROOM AT THE UNLOADING FACILITY TO CALL 911 AS THIS FACILITY IS UNMANNED UNTIL 5:00 AM.  THE DRIVER THEN GOT BACK UNDER THE SAFETY SHOWER UNTIL THE AMBULANCE ARRIVED.  JERRY HOSACK HAD SOME OTHER HEALTH PROBLEM THAT WHERE IDENTIFIED WHERE HE WAS IN THE HOSPITAL.  JERRY HOSACK HAD SOME OTHER HEALTH PROBLEM THAT WHERE IDENTIFIED WHILE HE WAS IN THE HOSPITAL.  JERRY HOSACK WAS IN THE ICU BURN UNIT FOR 17 DAYS.  TAMPA GENERAL HOSPITAL HAD DONE SKIN GRAFTING TO THE BURNS AREAS.  ON THE 17TH DAY IS WHEN JERRY HOSACK EXPIRED.  IT IS NOT KNOWN AT THIS TIME IF THE ACID BURNS CAUSED HIS DEATH OR IF THEY'RE WERE OTHER HEALTH RELATED ISSUES.  THE AUTOPSY REPORT WAS NOT AVAILABLE AT THE TIME THIS REPORT WAS PREPARED.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO OSHA IN TAMPA, FL TO EDWARD NORTON THE AREA SUPERVISOR.

13:50 DRIVER NOTICED SMALL AMOUNT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL ON TOP OF 2 DRUMS DURING HIS FREIGHT SECUREMENT CHECK.  TRAILER DOORS WERE CLOSED AND THE DRIVER CALLED CHEMTREC.  CHEMTREC THEN CALLED DISPATCH AND DROPPED THE CALL TO THE DISPATCHER.  DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED TO NOTIFY THE TRUCK STOP MANAGER, KEEP PEOPLE AWAY AND WAIT FOR EMERGENCY RESPONDER.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND THE EMERGENCY PHONE NUMBER FROM THE BOL WAS CALLED AGAIN. THE SHIPPER STATED TO CALL THE EMERGENCY NUMBER, SINCE THAT WAS ALREADY DONE, WE ASKED FOR THE MSDS SHEETS FOR ALL MATERIALS ON THE TRAILER.  AT THE SAME TIME, THE EMERGENCY PHONE NUMBER THAT WAS CALLED WAS ALSO CALLING THE SHIPPER FOR THE MSDS.  PAT PIETREFESA AT THE SHIPPER WAS NOT VERY HELPFUL.  HE WANTED TO KNOW WHY THE DRIVER WAS NOT FARTHER DOWN THE ROAD THAN HE WAS AND WHY THE DRIVER STOPPED AND WAS LOOKING AT THE FREIGHT.  HE WANTED TO KNOW WHAT AND HOW MANY DRUMS WERE LEAKING.  IT IS OUR POLICY TO NOT ALLOW THE DRIVER NEAR ANY LEAKING HAZARD CONTAINERS, DRIVER ARE TO KEEP PEOPLE AWAY AND CALL DISPATCH FOR PROFESSIONAL HELP ON ALL HAZARD LEAKS. WE CONTACTED XL AMERICA, INC. TO FIND A CLEAN UP COMPANY TO ACCESS THE SITUATION.  THE SHIPPER WAS ABLE TO FAX THE MSDS BY 13:25.  XL DISPATCHED WARREN FOX FROM HMHTTC, 610-458-7448.  ETA WAS 45 MINUTES.  15:15 MR. FOX WAS ON SCENE AND IT WAS DETERMINED FUMES WERE TOO STRONG TO ENTER THE TRAILER.  PAT PITREFESA FROM THE SHIPPER WAS ALSO AT THE TRUCK STOP AND WAS TRYING TO ENTER THE TRAILER.  MR. FOX HAD TO PREVENT HIM FROM GETTING INTO THE BOX.  BY THE TIME THE FUMES HAD DISSIPATED ENOUGH, MR. FOX ENTERED THE TRAILER AND FOUND 2 DRUMS BUNG LIDS WERE NOT TIGHT ENOUGH.  ANY MATERIAL THAT HAD SEEPED DURING TRANSPORTATION HAD DISSIPATED AND NO CLEAN UP WAS NEEDED.  17:00 THE VEHICLE WAS EN-ROUTE TO THE CONSIGNEE AND SAFELY DELIVERED.

LEE HAMMOND, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, NOTIFIED LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF TANK CAR GATX 300464 WHICH WAS REPORTED TO BE LEAKING IN EAST MINNEAPOLIS, MN. MR. SEKAVEC MADE CONTACT WITH MIKE KOSCINSKI, SPECIAL AGENT HAZ-MAT, AS WELL AS ALEX MCLEAN, PROJECT MANAGER HULCHER SERVICES, TO PERFORM AN INSPECTION ON THE TANK CAR. MR. KOSCINSKI REPORTED A LEAK AT THE A-END OF THE TANK CAR. HE ADVISED THE LEAK APPEARED TO BE COMING FROM A CRACK IN THE TANK SHELL. MR. SEKAVEC REQUESTED THAT MR. MCLEAN AND MR. KOSCINSKI RE-INSPECT THE CAR TO VERIFY THAT THERE WE NO OTHER LOCATIONS ON THE CAR THAT COULD BE PROVIDING A FALSE INDICATION OF THE LEAK LOCATION. THEY REPORTED BACK TO MR. SEKAVEC THAT THERE WERE NO OTHER LOCATIONS ON THE CAR THAT WERE RELEASING PRODUCT. MR. SEKAVEC WAS IN CONTACT WITH LINDA SALINAS, TEXMARK (SHIPPER), WHO ADVISED SHE WOULD ATTEMPT TO LOCATE A SUITABLE TANK CAR TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT INTO. MR. SEKAVEC ALSO CONTACTED GARY SEVERSON WITH INTERPLASTIC (CONSIGNEE) TO ADVISE HIM OF THE PROBLEM AND DETERMINE IF THERE WAS A USABLE TANK CAR SPOTTED AT INTERPLASTIC THAT COULD BE ACCESSED. ACCORDING TO MR. SEVERSON, UTLX 644215 WAS SCHEDULED TO BE PULLED AND WOULD BE A SUITABLE TANK CAR FOR THE TRANSFER. MR. SEKAVEC RELAYED THE INFORMATION TO MR. KOSCINSKI AND ASKED THAT MR. KOSCINSKI ARRANGE WITH THE LOCAL TRANSPORTATION EMPLOYEES FOR MOVEMENT OF THE CAR BACK TO THE EAST MINNEAPOLIS YARD. LATE IN THE AFTERNOON OF SEPTEMBER 6, THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED WITH NO COMPLICATIONS., APPROXIMATELY TWENTY-FIVE GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS ESTIMATED TO BE SPILLED. MORE ACCURATE AMOUNTS ARE IMPOSSIBLE TO OBTAIN BUT BASED ON THE EXTREME ODOR AND SMALL AMOUNT ACTUALLY BEING RELEASED, IT APPEARS THAT A FAIRLY SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED. ON SEPTEMBER 10, TONY LVASKEVICIUS, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, INSPECTED THE AREA AND THE TANK CAR. MR. LVASKEVICIUS ADVISED THERE WAS NO ODOR IN THE AREA, INDICATING NO FURTHER CLEAN-UP OF THE TRACK WAS NEEDED. NO LONG-TERM REMEDIATION OF THE AREA IS EXPECTED.

RMCC CONTACTED CTS MGR. M KELLY AND ADVISED THAT NATX 29654 LOCATED IN THE YARD IN ODESSA TX. WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR. INSPECTION OF THE CAR REVEALED THAT THE BOLTS ON THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE WERE LOOSE ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPLASH OUT ONTO THE TOP OF THE CAR. THE BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED. THE CAR WAS THEN INSPECTED AND RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

column62: Derailment; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TIM BESSERMA, ASSISTANT TRAIN MASTER FOR ALTON AND SOUTHERN RAILROAD EAST ST LOUIS, IL, REPORTED TANKCAR UTLX 48044 WAS ON FIRE IN THE ALTON SOUTHERN RAILYARD. OPERATOR 23, EAST ST LOUIS EMERGENCY DISPATCHER, WAS NOTIFIED AND FIRE CREWS WERE ENROUTE. JOHN MILLER, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. ON THE NORTH SIDE OF ALTON AND SOUTHERN YARD, A THREE BLOCK RADIUS WAS PREPARED FOR EVACUATION. NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE. AT 05:25 AM, MGR MILLER REPORTED THE INCIDENT OCCURRED AT THE HUMP, WITH TWO RAILCARS BURNING. CTEH WAS NOTIFIED AND A TEAM WAS RESPONDING. AT 08:32 AM, JOHN MILLER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, ADVISED THERE WAS STILL RESIDUAL FIRE IN THE AREA CONTAINED TO RAILROAD TIES, WHICH WOULD BE FOAMED. MR. MILLER STATED THE FIRE ON THE RAILCARS WAS DYING DOWN AND PERSONNEL WOULD ATTEMPT TO RE-EXTINGUISH THE FIRE. AT 11:34 AM, RMCC WAS NOTIFIED THAT TANKCAR ACFX 71703 WAS EXTINGUISHED, AND MGR MILLER, HULCHER SERVICES, CONTRACTOR, AND STATE AND FEDERAL PERSONNEL, WERE MEETING TO DEVISE A PLAN OF REMEDIATION. AT 03:42 PM, MGR MILLER ADVISED THE PLAN WAS BEING FINALIZED FOR HANDLING TANKCAR UTLX 200817, AND HE BELIEVED THEY WOULD FLARE IT OFF, WITHOUT TRANSLOADING THE PRODUCT. MR. MILLER ADVISED ALL EVACUATIONS WERE LIFTED ON 07:30 AM. AT. AT 10:30 PM. MGR MILLER ADVISED THREE UPRIGHT DERAILED RAILCARS WERE RERAILED AND MOVED. TANKCAR UTLX 200817 WOULD BE FLARED OFF THROUGHOUT THE NIGHT AND UPON COMPLETION THE REMAINING TWO RAILCARS WOULD BE RERAILED AND YARD RESTORATION WOULD COMMENCE. MR. MILLER FURTHER STATED THE FEDERAL, STATE, AND EPA AGENCIES REMAINED ON SCENE ALONG WITH GLEN THOMAS, DIRECTOR OF ENVIRONMENTAL OPERATIONS. ON 09/22/04 AT 2:24 PM, MGR MILLER REPORTED THE FIRE ON TANKCAR UTLX 200817 WAS EXTINGUISHED AND THE TANKCAR HAD BEEN CLEANED AND PURGED. MR. MILLER STATED TANKCAR ACFX 71703 WAS RERAILED AND SOME TRACK REPAIR HAD BEGUN. MR. MILLER ADVISED TOM POWELL, ILLINOIS ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY, DISCOVERED SOME PRODUCT HAD ENTERED THE STORM DRAINS. ON 09/22/04 AT 9:48 PM, MILLER REPORTED TANKCAR UTLX 200817 WAS RERAILED AND FULL TRACK REBUILDING WAS IN PROGRESS. CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS BEING EXCAVATED FOR DISPOSAL TOMORROW. THE STORM DRAINS ARE BEING PURGED WITH CLEAN WATER AND THE WATER CAPTURED FOR DISPOSAL AT THE OTHER END OF THE DRAIN SYSTEM. ON 09/23, AT 06:06 AM, MILLER REPORTED THE LAST TRACK PANELS WERE BEING APPLIED AND THE EXCAVATION OF CONTAMINATED SOIL HAD BEEN COMPLETED. MR. MILLER STATED THE CLEANUP CREW WOULD RESUME FLUSHING OUT THE STORM DRAINS AT 07:00 AM.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Basic Material; Piping or Fittings
column168: VERN LIBBY, SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT, REPORTED CONTAINER NOSU 436510 LEAKING AT THE YARD IN SEATTLE, WA. NO WATER WAYS WERE AFFECTED. MR. LIBBY CONTRACTED NRC REMEDIATION TO RESPOND. NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE STATE OF WASHINGTON. THE CONTAINER WAS LOCATED IN LANE 3 AT THE NORTHEND INTERCHANGE GATE, SEATTLE YARD. LIBBY RESPONDED AND A PH TEST REFLECTED A PH READING OF 0. THE CONTAINER WAS ISOLATED AND LANE 3 WAS CLOSED UNTIL IT COULD BE DECONTAMINATED. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THE CONTENT OF CONTAINER NOSU 436510 HAD BEEN TRANSLOADED FROM CONTAINER TGHU 721064 ON 09/27/2004 AT SEATTLE, WA. FURTHER AT TIME OF TRANSLOAD CONTAINER NOSU 436510 WAS BLOCKED AND BRACED BY NRC EMPLOYEES. NRC WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE LEAKING NOSU CONTAINER. CHEMTREC WAS THEN CONTRACTED AND REPORT # 09/292004 067 WAS ASSIGNED TO THIS INCIDENT. NOSU 436510 WAS TRANSLOADED FROM TGHU 721064 09/27/2004. MATT CHANEY, NRC HAD HIS FORCES CLEAN AND NEUTRALIZE INTERCHANGE GATE LANE 3 UPON ARRIVAL. NOSU 436510 WAS OPENED AND BLOCKING AND BRACING WAS REMOVED FROM DOORWAY. NRC REMOVED THE 330 GALLON TOTES ONE AT A TIME CHECKING FOR THE LEAK. FURTHER AS THEY WERE REMOVED, THE TOTES WERE TRANSLOADED TO A TRAILER OWNED BY CASCADE COLUMBIA DIST. SEATTLE, WA. (FINAL CONSIGNEE). AGAIN ONE OF 14 OF THE TOTES WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING IN THE AREA OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, IN WHAT APPEARED TO BE THE SAME MANOR AS THE LEAKING TOTE FOUND IN CONTAINER THGU 721064 09/327/2004. AGAIN THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TOTE AND ALSO LOADED INTO CASCADE COLUMBIA'S TRAILER. WHEN EMPTY NOSU 436510 WAS MADE SAFE FOR OVER THE ROAD TRAVEL, IT WAS RELEASED TO CASCADE COLUMBIA FOR ADDITIONAL CLEANING AND NEUTRALIZATION. PREVIOUS INCIDENT INVOLVING CONTAINER TGHU 721064 WAS COVERED BY 5800.1 REPORT # 5464.

DAVE BLAZEJEWSKI, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, ADVISED WHILE THE CREW OF TRAIN YAV52 29 WAS PERFORMING A LOCAL SWITCHING JOB, THEY REPORTED TWO OF THE THREE CREW MEMBERS SMELLED SULFUR IN THE AIR AND ADVISED THEY WERE SUFFERING FROM BURNING OF EYES, DRYNESS OF THE MOUTH, AND NAUSEA. MR BLAZEJEWSKI STATED HE AND CO-WORKER WALKED THE AREA OF THE INCIDENT AND SMELLED A MINOR ODOR, BUT NOTHING STRONG . AT 09:05 PM, THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT. AT 09:23 PM, TOBY TREVETT, SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, REQUESTED RMCC CONTACT THE DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC SAFETY TO MAKE NECESSARY NOTIFICATION. SAHM TREVETT ADVISED THAT UPON FURTHER INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED RAILCAR CCBX 40053 RELEASED PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE ONTO THE BALLAST. TREVETT ALSO ADVISED THE TRAIN CREW OF TRAIN YAV52 29 REFUSED MEDICAL TREATMENT AND REPORTED THEY WOULD SEEK MEDICAL ASSISTANCE FROM THEIR OWN PHYSICIAN IF SYMPTOMS WERE PREVALENT. THE NORTH SECTION OF THE YARD WAS CLOSED UNTIL THE INCIDENT COULD BE CLEARED. CTEH NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE FOR THE PURPOSE OF PROVIDING INFORMATION TO THE CREW IF NEEDED. AT 11:00 PM, ROBERT CAZES, DOW CHEMICAL, ADVISED THAT A CREW WAS BEING DISPATCHED TO HANDLE THE REMEDIATION OF SPILLED PRODUCT. AT  11:28 PM, TONY CTEH, WAS NOTIFIED AND CONFERRED RMCC WITH DR. GANDY. DR GANDY WAS ADVISED OF THE SUBSTANCE DESCRIPTION AND UN CLASSIFICATION. DR. GANDY REQUESTED RMCC ATTEMPT TO SECURE THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (MSDS) FOR THE PRODUCT. DR. GANDY REQUESTED AGENT TREVETT TAKE AND DOCUMENT AIR SAMPLE READINGS AT THE INCIDENT LOCATION. AT 01:26 AM, THE MSDS SHEET WAS RECEIVED FROM DOW CHEMICAL, VIA FACSIMILE, AND FORWARDED TO DR. GANDY, VIA FACSIMILE. AT 02:01 AM, SAHM TREVETT REPORTED THAT DOW CHEMICAL REPRESENTATIVES ARRIVED ON SCENE AND HAD LOCATED LOOSE PACKING IN THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND REPAIRS WERE IN PROGRESS. REMEDIATION OF THE LOCATION WAS COMPLETED AT 02:40 AM, WITH YARD RETURNED TO FULL SERVICE. REMEDIATED PRODUCT WAS COLLECTED BY THE DOW CHEMICAL REPRESENTATIVES AND REMOVED FOR PROPER DISPOSAL. AGENT TREVETT ADVISED RAILCAR CCBX 400053 WAS PLACED IN BAD ORDER STATUS AND DOW CHEMICAL PERSONNEL WOULD CONTACT THE OPERATING DEPARTMENT TO MAKE ARRANGEMENTS FOR THE RAILCARS RETURN TO THE DOW PLANT.

WHILE MAKING A PICK-UP OF SPENT CUPRIC CHLORIDE ON 9/22/04, THE TANKER TRAILER AIR DIAPHRAGM PUMP HAD A FLANGE FITTING FAILURE THAT RESULTED IN A RELEASE OF PRODUCT IN THE LOADING BAY AT COMPEQ INTERNATIONAL, MIKE KOMIS, UNIVAR DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE AIR AND TANKER FILL VALVES, NOTIFIED COMPEQ'S WASTEWATER TECHNICIANS AND BEGAN CONTAINING THE SPILLED PRODUCT. HE WAS ABLE TO PREVENT ANY OFF SITE MIGRATION BY PLACING CHEMICAL ABSORBENT SOCKS AT THE LOW SPOT WHILE THE COMPEQ TECHNICIANS ASSISTED IN MOPPING UP THE RELEASE.  THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED AT 4:00 PM, MST.  MIKE NOTIFIED ME, BOB SOLLESVIK, OF THE INCIDENT AT 4:10 PM MST.  I THEN CONTACTED MY REGIONAL OPERATIONS MANAGER, CHARLY BONNIE AND DISTRICT MANAGER, LARRY DAVIS BEFORE PROCEEDING TO THE SPILL SITE.  UPON ARRIVAL I MET TED WITTE, COMPEQ INTERNATIONAL ADMINISTRATIVE MANAGER WHO WAS OVERSEEING THE CLEAN-UP.  MOST OF THE RAW PRODUCT HAD BEEN RECOVERED INTO THE LARGE CATCH BASIN BELOW THE CHEMICAL FILL FITTINGS.  THE COMPEQ EMPLOYEES HAD ALREADY WASHED DOWN THE TRUCK, CONCRETE RAMP AND DRIVE AND WERE MOPPING UP AS I WAS TAKING PICTURES AND REVIEWING THE DAMAGED PUMP.  THE RECLAIMED MIXTURE OF SPENT CUPRIC CHLORIDE AND WATER, (APPROX. 80-90 GAL.), WAS TRANSFERRED TO THE TANKER AFTER REPAIRS WERE MADE TO THE PUMP.  ROOT CAUSE: THERE ARE THREE POSSIBLE SCENARIOS THAT COULD HAVE CONTRIBUTED TO THIS INCIDENT.  1. THE OUTLET CONNECTION ON THE T/T PUMP HAD A 1 1/2" NIPPLE BETWEEN THE FLANGE AND THE 2" CAMLOCK FITTING.  WITH EACH CONTINUOUS CAVITATION OF THE PUMP, THERE IS A TREMENDOUS AMOUNT OF PRESSURE AND VIBRATION THAT OVER TIME CAN WEAKEN THE PVC FITTING CAUSING IT TO SNAP.  A SUPPORT FOR THE HOSE COULD ALLEVIATE THIS.  2.  THE 1 1/2" NIPPLE BETWEEN THE OUTLET FLANGE AND 2" CAMLOCK FITTING WAS BOTTOMED OUT AND GLUED TO THE FLANGE WHICH COULD HAVE BEEN TO STOP PREVIOUS LEAKING OR LOOSENESS OF THE THREADS.  3.  HAVING A 1 1/2" PUMP BETWEEN 2" SUCTION AND DISCHARGE HOSES COULD BE CONTRIBUTING TO THE HIGH FLOW PRESSURE ON THE DISCHARGE SIDE.  A 2" PUMP COULD ALLEVIATE THIS BY HAVING A CONSISTENT FLOW FROM THE SUPPLY TANK TO THE TANKER TRAILER.  CORRECTIVE ACTION:  AFTER A REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT WITH THE UNIVAR SAFETY COMMITTEE, WE HAVE DETERMINED THE MOST REASONABLE CAUSE FOR THE FITTING FAILURE WAS DUE TO STRESS PLACED ON THE OUTLET CONNECTION OF THE TRANSFER HOSE.  WE HAVE CONTACTED OUR HOSE SUPPLIER TO MODIFY THE CURRENT HOSE BY SHORTENING IT TO LESSEN THE STRESS ON THE PUMP CONNECTIONS AND WILL HAVE BRACE INSTALLED TO SUPPORT THE OUTLET FLANGE SIMILAR TO THE INLET CONNECTION.  WE WILL TEST THE PROCESS BEFORE OUR NEXT SCHEDULED PICK UP TO INSURE IT'S SAFE OPERABILITY.  SIDE NOTE: AFTER REPLACING THE EXISTING DISCHARGE HOSE WITH A SHORTER LENGTH AND REPLACING THE OUTLET FLANGE FITTINGS, WE TESTED THE PUMP AND NOTICED A SIZEABLE LESSENING OF PRESSURE AND TORQUE ON THE OUTLET FLANGE.  WILL MOVE FORWARD ON BRACING THE FLANGE AND CONTINUE TO MONITOR THE CHANGES.
